description:
Create src/bus/types.spade with all bus interface types from §12.2.

CPU-facing bus contract (minimal, §12.2):
  enum BusReq { Idle, Read{addr: uint<16>}, Write{addr: uint<16>, data: uint<8>} }
  struct BusResp { data: uint<8> }

Simulation-only observation sideband (§12.2.1):
  enum BusRegion { Rom, Vram, CartRam, Wram, Echo, Oam, NotUsable, Io, Hram, Ie }
  struct BusObs { region: BusRegion, blocked: bool, owner: BusOwner }

Bus ownership (§12.2.2):
  enum BusOwner { Cpu, OamDma, Ppu, Idle }

DESIGN PRINCIPLES:
- CPU always emits plain BusReq. DMA/PPU contention resolved in fabric, NOT in CPU (§12.2.2)
- BusObs is for commit traces and diagnostics only. Do NOT widen CPU bus contract until concrete need (§12.2.1)
- Keep it simple initially. Add complexity only when Wave C (DMA/MBC) requires it
- BusReq::Idle ensures quiescent buses when no access needed (§18.3 power)

Create src/cpu/types.spade with all core CPU types from §7.2 and §8.1-8.2.

Architectural state (§7.1A):
  enum ImeState { Disabled, PendingEnable, Enabled }
  enum HaltState { Running, Halted, HaltBugPending }
  struct CpuArchState { regs: Registers, ime_state: ImeState, halt_state: HaltState }

Microstate (§7.1B):
  struct CpuMicroState { phase: Phase, opcode_latch: uint<8>, imm_lo: uint<8>, imm_hi: uint<8>, decoded: DecodedOp, temp: uint<16> }
  struct CpuState { arch: CpuArchState, micro: CpuMicroState }

Phase enum (§8.1) — the type system makes illegal combinations impossible:
  enum PrefixKind { Cb }
  enum Phase {
    Fetch,
    FetchPrefix { prefix: PrefixKind },
    ReadImm8 { k: Imm8Cont },
    ReadImm16Lo { k: Imm16Cont },
    ReadImm16Hi { lo: uint<8>, k: Imm16HiCont },
    ReadMem { addr: uint<16>, k: ReadCont },
    WriteMem { addr: uint<16>, data: uint<8>, k: WriteCont },
    Execute { op: DecodedOp },
    ServiceInterrupt { irq: IrqSel, subphase: IrqPhase },
    Halted,
  }

Continuation enums (§8.2) — carry semantic intent in the type:
  enum ReadCont { LoadReg8{dst: R8}, LoadAFromAddr, AluFromMem{kind: AluKind}, PopLo{pair: RegPair}, PopHi{pair: RegPair, lo: uint<8>} }
  enum WriteCont { StoreDone, PushHi{next_pc: uint<16>}, PushLo{low: uint<8>, target: uint<16>} }

Sparse delta type (§7.2, §18.4 — critical for power):
  struct CpuDelta { regs_write: RegWriteSet, pc_write: Option<uint<16>>, sp_write: Option<uint<16>>, ime_write: Option<ImeState>, halt_write: Option<HaltState>, micro_write: MicroWriteSet }

Semantic step interface (§7.2):
  fn step_mcycle(state: CpuState, input: MicroInput) -> MicroOutput
  fn apply_delta(state: CpuState, delta: CpuDelta) -> CpuState

DESIGN NOTE: The exact spellings may evolve during implementation. What matters is: typed continuations, sparse deltas, three-layer state split. HaltBugPending is designed in now but can be a stub until the interrupt milestone (§8.3).
